# Are Humans Responsible for Climate Change? A Comprehensive Analysis

Climate change is one of the most pressing global challenges of the 21st century. The question of whether humans are responsible for climate change has been extensively studied, debated, and analyzed across multiple scientific disciplines. This report aims to provide a detailed, well-structured, and comprehensive examination of the evidence regarding human responsibility for climate change, drawing on the most recent and reliable scientific sources available up to 2025.

---

## Scientific Consensus on Human-Caused Climate Change

The overwhelming majority of climate scientists agree that human activities are the primary driver of recent global warming. Multiple large-scale studies analyzing peer-reviewed scientific literature have consistently found a consensus exceeding 99% that anthropogenic (human-caused) factors are responsible for climate change.

- A landmark study published in *Environmental Research Letters* in 2021 analyzed nearly 90,000 climate-related scientific papers published between 2012 and 2020. It found that more than 99.9% of these papers endorsed the view that human activities are the main cause of climate change ([Lea, 2021](https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/technology/scientific-consensus-is-clear-humans-cause-climate-change-ahead-of-cop26-summit/ar-AAPL4tX)).

- Earlier studies, such as the 2013 review of research from 1991 to 2012, found a 97% consensus on anthropogenic climate change ([ScienceDaily, 2021](https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2021/10/211019082702.htm)).

- Surveys of climate scientists also support this consensus. For example, a 2009 survey by Doran and Zimmerman found 97.4% agreement among actively publishing climate scientists that humans are causing global warming. This figure increased to 98.7% in a 2021 follow-up survey ([Monash Lens, 2021](https://lens.monash.edu/@science/2021/10/21/1383952/the-scientific-consensus-on-climate-change-gets-even-stronger)).

| Study/Survey | Period Covered | Consensus Percentage | Notes |
|--------------|----------------|----------------------|-------|
| Cook et al. (2013) | 1991-2012 | 97% | Based on 12,000+ abstracts |
| Lynas et al. (2021) | 2012-2020 | >99.9% | Nearly 90,000 papers analyzed |
| Doran & Zimmerman (2009) | Survey | 97.4% | Among active climate scientists |
| Doran et al. (2021) | Survey | 98.7% | Updated survey of Earth scientists |

This near-unanimous agreement among experts indicates that the scientific community views human influence on climate as a settled fact, with little room left for meaningful debate.

