## Evidence Supporting Anthropogenic Climate Change

### 1. Radiative Forcing and Greenhouse Gas Emissions

Radiative forcing refers to the change in energy balance in the Earth's atmosphere due to factors such as greenhouse gases (GHGs). Human activities, primarily the burning of fossil fuels, deforestation, and industrial processes, have significantly increased concentrations of GHGs like carbon dioxide (CO₂), methane (CH₄), and nitrous oxide (N₂O).

- Since the pre-industrial era (circa 1850-1900), atmospheric CO₂ levels have risen from approximately 280 parts per million (ppm) to over 420 ppm in 2025, levels unprecedented in at least two million years ([Climate Council, 2021](https://www.climatecouncil.org.au/resources/what-does-ipcc-latest-report-mean/)).

- Radiative forcing from anthropogenic GHGs is the dominant driver of the observed warming, with natural factors such as solar irradiance and volcanic activity playing a minor or cooling role overall ([Stern & Kaufmann, 2014](https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10584-013-1007-x)).

- The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) Sixth Assessment Report (2021) states unequivocally that human influence has warmed the atmosphere, ocean, and land, with a confidence level exceeding 95% ([IPCC, 2021](https://ideas.ted.com/new-sixth-ipcc-report-on-climate-change-key-takeaways/)).

### 2. Attribution Studies and Climate Models

Attribution studies use climate models and statistical methods to distinguish human-induced warming from natural variability.

- Multiple independent studies have concluded that the observed warming since the mid-20th century cannot be explained by natural factors alone. Instead, human activities are responsible for virtually all of the global surface temperature increase observed since 1950 ([Skeptical Science, 2021](https://skepticalscience.com/ipcc-human-caused-global-warming-attribution-confidence.htm)).

- Climate models that include only natural forcings fail to reproduce the observed warming trend, whereas models that include anthropogenic forcings match observations closely.

### 3. Paleoclimate Evidence

Paleoclimate data provide context for current warming trends by reconstructing past climate changes.

- The rate and magnitude of recent warming far exceed natural climate variations observed over the past several millennia ([Chan, 2021](https://chandarren97.medium.com/the-evidence-for-anthropogenic-climate-change-f5c6f2a48b85)).

- Natural cycles such as the Milankovitch cycles, solar variability, and volcanic eruptions have influenced climate over geological timescales but cannot account for the rapid warming observed in recent decades.

